name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
Nice to find shady trails with some elevation.  It's difference vibes compared to my other favorite trails in East Coast Park, it's much more woodsy here and climbing to the summit provides up and down trails.

While I was planning to continue to Dairy Farm Nature Park after the Summit, that was not possible as the trail to the Dairy Farm is closed (both upper and lower loop trails).  Within The Bukit Timah Nature Reserve, a large portion of Jungle Fall Path is also closed off for maintenance.  See photos posted for closure details.

I opted to detour through South View Path on the way to the Summit and was rewarded with quieter trail, albeits lots of staircase up and down.  Also, took the staircase to the Summit instead of winding through the main trail.  It's steep but thankfully shorter distance.

Took the main trail down to the park exit - after a detour due to closure of Dairy Farm Loop and Jungle Fall Path trails.

It's one of my favorite trails - shady trails and lots of birds and large trees.

PS: The visitor centre is just OK but the vending machines sell a good selection of cold drinks.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
Bukit Timah Nature Resserve is a great nature treasure well preserved for posterity. Great place to exercise amidst nature. üëçüåü.

If you are lucky, you get to see exotic birds , the monitor lizards and of course chicken running around in the jungle.

Before you start your hike, kindly ensure that you are well hydrated and have used the restroom if necessary. Once you are on your way up, you won't find water until you return to base station.

The steep slope UP üÜô‚¨ÜÔ∏è can be a bit of a challenge if you are not fit and so are the stairs for those who are not used to rigours of a climb.

What i did not like about this place  was the tarred road going up/ down was and is not well maintained üëéüëé. It was easy to trip / sprain your ankle unless you were careful. In addition  there are dry leaves and it could potentially lead to a skidding misadventure. I really wish the tarred areas are well maintained and the dry leaves are cleared in time.

Just as much as I love this wonderful Nature Reserve, I also hope that the tarred road up/ down is well maintained, in addition to clearing of the dried leaves.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: I took public transport from downtown to come to this hiking trail. It was a nice trail, easy-medium level. I saw a lot of monkeys on the way back. Only few people were doing this hike on a weekday.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: In my opinion, this nature reserve (free entrance) located in the West of Singapore has the best hiking terrain in Singapore for those who wished to train for adventure hikes. For those who want to take an easier trail, just take the road path all the way up to the summit (the steeper part is just in the beginning 200m or so). This can be done in under 30 mins for most people with moderate stamina. There are also cycling paths for those who are more adventurous.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Beautiful Nature Reserve - The first part of walking was the toughest - since the slope was very steep - Highly recommend taking a water bottle, mosquito patch and some sunscreen - The entire walk is very beautiful  especially listening to the sounds of the birds and insects - Watch out for Monkeys - There are different trails to walk  - follow the maps which are setup through the trail - There are also benches available at different location to sit and relax - Very difficult to go if it‚Äôs raining - MRT is walkable distance - There is also a nice car park available - Just near the visitor centre there is a restroom and drinking water available

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
The most exciting and challenging part of our journey today.

The walk up to the summit at the beginning stage was steep with about 50 degree gradient incline.

The climbing of the stairs was quite hectic due to the steep climb and uneven steps. But there is an alternatr and easier path on the main road for other users.

The view of the summit include communication towers, a huge resting area and popular stone landmark indicating the height, longtitude and latitude of the summit for many to take picture with.

The good thing about this place is that there are several resting along the way up so that you could take a short break before continuing.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
Found another access overhead bridge. From Beauty World Food Centre out from escalator will saw the overhead bridge and walked straight passed by 2 shops. Down overhead bridge walked straight passed by another overhead bridge walked straight then at road junction turn left walked up passed by Le Wood. Have attached photos of where the overhead bridge located.

Before started hiking went to washroom first,which located at the foot of the hill. First 1/3 is the super steep up slope. Really steep,awhile reached Kruing Hut. After that the slope is no longer that super steep. This 2/3 slope until the end is with drinage. Roughly took me 30mins to reach the Summit as I turned to another slope and turned back.

Going down the hill for the 2/3 slope is not very steep. But for the 1/3 super steep slope is scary of going down.

My next visit will visit Hindhere Quarry after hiking as it will reopened on 01/10/2022

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: The highest natural peak one can go in Singapore. Nice climb up with various route options, slope or stairs and even a track for mountain bikers. Toilet and water coolers at the foot of the hill for stock up before and replenish after. A few huts with benches also allow rest points along the way. However the peak is a little underwhelming, can consider building a viewing gallery for people to see the view from up there and also more sheds at the summit would be great as it can get crowded. Also parking space is very limited, so be prepared to wait for parking if you‚Äôre driving there. Overall, still a nice mildly challenging climb, suitable even for elderly and young children üëçüí™

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: The Best Experience of Singapore.If you want to trek so this is the best place to explore.View is really amazing . The highest natural peak one can go in Singapore. Nice climb up with various route options, slope or stairs and even a track for mountain bikers.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
I had a great hike. Thanks to the MRT, I was able to take a train to Beautyworld station, followed by a short 7mins walk to the location. The hardest part was the starting portion where the path forward was a very steep upward slope. Once you conquer that, the rest of the hike was very manageable.

Pay attention to the sudden sightings of the monitor lizards and wild mushrooms!

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Steep moderate climb to summit... Although shortcut  stairs near to top are killer, avoid if possible... However  well worth the journey using the road... Many Monkeys playing in the trees above at the radio tower.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Really good place to enjoy nature and have a relaxing start to the weekend! I managed to make the climb up the hill and also went to the hindhede quarry to try my luck spotting some rare birds!

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Highest hill in sg! Multiple trails. We did the steep upslope and some stairs in 1 hr and no detour. Good recovery training and didnt have time to try the newly open rifle range! Maybe next time. More monkeys during this visit not sure if its was due to less crowd

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
Reaching BTNR is easy from MRT station DT5 to Hindhede entrance, or DT3 DairyFarm entrance.

Once in the forest, even on sunny days, the walk through canopy covered trail is pleasantly cool.

All the trails are good for rainy day treks and BTNR is dotted with rest huts, good for shelter should rain gets too heavy.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Wonderful getaway in a city life like Singapore. Good balance of nature and yet having clear path and safety for hikers. Beautiful & don't miss it ‚ù§Ô∏è

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Feels and look unlike any other place in Singapore. The lake in the quarry felt like I was in a different country. Such a peaceful and serene location. Can just sit there for hours looking at all the small turtles swimming merrily in the water. The reflection of the towers on the water is so cool. Must visit - can combine with a hike to Bukit Timah Hill.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
Entah siape lah yang desain slope yang mula2 start tu. Macam steep sangat. Taccod tau boleh tergolek! Termengah-mengah dibuatnye mendaki bukit.

Tapi tu lah, we didn‚Äôt know that it was super accessible via Beauty World MRT, just a few minutes walk and we already at the entrance.

We went there about 7.30am and the weather was really cooling. It was a Sunday and the crowd was not that many I would say. But when going back, we saw a lot more people so i would recommend going early on a weekend.

For those looking for a parking space, don‚Äôt drive there. The parking was full and the queue was long, so best to just go there via public transport.

There‚Äôre multiple routes you can explore, which we did. We didn‚Äôt know where we were going but it was still a fun trekking session and you wont get lost as long as you stay within the walking path.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: A great place for a hike and to get away from the city . There are different trails to choose from depending on your fitness  but all are achievable.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
One of the few nature walks in Singapore. Compared to other countries, it's nothing impressive but there's really not alot of nature in tiny urbanized Singapore.

15 mins from the starting point to the summit and another 15 mins down. You'll feel safe, paths are clearly marked.

Trails are almost full tarmac with steps. Not much views. The trees provided plenty of shade and I feel it's not too hot.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Our usual weekend morning exercise place but it can be quite crowded also. Better take the trails as they are less crowded. Good to hike between Dairy Farm Nature Park and Bukit Timah Nature Park since it is more challenging. They should have some toilet up in the mountain as I never see one after the entrance.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Beautiful trail with multiple route options to schooner from as per your strength and liking.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Trekked through the lush tropical forest and enjoyed the charming biodiversity. Rush not but listen to the whispers of nature üòÅ

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Nice outdoor for the whole family. you can just have a nice stroll along the paved walking track or go hiking on the hiking trail for those who are more adventurous. Great place to come to work out some sweat or just to get away ay from the hustle and bustle. Ample parking on non peak hours. Best to avoid going on weekends when it can get quite crowded.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
It a nice place for light hiking and exercise.
I sweat a lot when go up and down. Cause I don't exercise regularly..,,üòÜüòÑ

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Insane hiking experience here. The starting point from the carpark was such a steep slope. Please be careful as you might hurt your knee. The path to the dairy farm is also closed, please take note!

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
Bukit Timah is good for exercise or for a leisure walk

You can choose your route based on the level of difficulty.

Challenge on difficulty route was mostly the hundreds of steps which you need to take uphill. Nevertheless, i always enjoy coming to this place rain or shine :)

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
We always go here if we want to run and or ride our mountain bikes. The trees are super old and tall. The weather here is great even when hot summer. But if your not a fan of nature definitely you won‚Äôt enjoy walking here hahaha!

Recommended for all those who love great nature and green pastures.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Great hike to the summit, a little steep but manageable with sheltered rest points along the way

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Very beautiful trail, quiet, natural and very well managed. Has lot many tracks to reach on top. On the way you can spot monkeys, wild pig, squirrels and many other small creatures. A very good cardiovascular exercise place to be in.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
One of Singapore‚Äôs few elevated hikes!

Despite a steep get-go, it was a relatively short hike to the summit, with a round trip lasting us less than an hour on the main route!

Well maintained trail, highly patronised by regular joggers, makes for a good get-away from the bustling city.

The only setback was that there wasn‚Äôt too much of a view at the top, considering the dense and tall vegetation all around the summit.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Nice place, if you want to have a short trucking experience, then this is one of the best place. climbing the mountain will a wonderful experience. Must go place in Singapore. When we went, we felt like a hill station due to the temperature and forest.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
An interesting nature reserve with a highlight of the highest natural point in Singapore (163.63m). The walking path is wide and solid with concrete.
Be warned that the first 700m from the visitor centre to the summit is a very steep incline path (it is not stairs and this is the steepest slope that I have seen in Singapore's nature reserves), it will be wise if you wear a proper shoes, not sandals.
It will be quite crowded in the weekend.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Good stream of early morning hiker. Today Sunday the 3rd of Jan 2021 the weather was cool. Great hike with friends. Did almost a 12km hike. The trail was a little wet due to the relentless rain the last couple of days. Super fun! Need to do this again soon.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Nice trails to take a walk. Love the lake scenery although it is quite hot and sunny right by the lake due to no shade at mid day, recommended to visit early if you want to enjoy this view. Also, trails might not be suitable for elders, but great for those who loves physical challengesüèÉ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüí™

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: A good place for families and friends to get close to nature while exercise leisurely. The roads and trails are well paved and maintained, safe and suitable for kids to explore. There are plenty of signages and maps around so navigation is easy. Overall an easy and family friendly nature reserve for most age groups so highly encourage everyone to give this place a try!

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: A place where you can get close with nature, quick escape from city life. There are different hiking routes to choose in order to get to the peak. Make sure to check the map for direction before walk too far away from destination. Get a bit crowded during weekend and public holiday. May come earlier to avoid the crowd.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: I'm a nature lover and I love to hike. This place has been restored to better facilitate nature lovers while hiking. There fews path you can choose from the simpler route to a more difficult route. Please take note the place can be over crowded usually over weekend especially during this pandemic of covid 19. Better time to go is very early morning or late afternoon  to avoid congestion.  I love the bigs steps so I will choose to walk inside the trail and take the steps. Make sure you bring rain coat especially during this unpredictable weather.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
Right off the bat the steepness of the uphill of Route 1 (classifies ‚Äúeasy‚Äù) knocked me breathless, and I realised how unfit I was. Years of sitting on my office chair for prolonged periods of time has taken its toll.

I‚Äôm grateful for the chance to hike up this hill, at least now I can strive to overcome it. Made it to the summit and felt really proud of myself.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: The tallest hill in Singapore at 163 metres high, this is the place for fitness and nature freaks, not for the faint at heart! If you just want to relax in the canopy of trees, you can come here, but beware of the monkeys! Wildlife is great and all information about the wildlife and trees there are available at the path

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: The place has been nicely done up!  The trails are reinforced and clearly marked.  Had a lovely morning walking up to the summit via the catchment trail. Great day too!  Cool morning after the previous wet weather. Saw some interesting plants and trees too.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Our first hike here in Singapore and we nailed it. 12km stretch in 2.5 hours. Beautiful scenes along the river bed as well as parts of jungle to go through. Loved it!!

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Good place for a leisurely walk , jog or hike. A cross country running trail during our younger days and now an adventure hike for middle agers hahaha. We also come across some soldiers ok their topo or navigation exercises, reminiscing my army days of trunching through the same forested areas and crossing insane swamps to get to that checkpoint, one of them is called hell.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: If you enjoy a nature appreciation walk, try the Bukit Timah walking trail. Bask in the beautiful greenery, cool air, chirping birds, carefree butterflies and steep steps. Be prepared for a little challenge if you are generally less active.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: It rained like a b but it was still so refreshing and fun. Good adventure, core memory. Steep slopes and giant steps made for perfect general monkeying.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: This place is good if you want to go for long walk with jungles surroundings and greener all over. Water reservior and the track is interesting and exiting. Good trip for excitement and fun.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Bukit Timah hill is the highest point in Singapore. Pristine, green and quite scenic. Path to hill is steep, but it is very short and easily doable. Also there are various other trails that one can do. Great for everyday walking routines and running too.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Really enjoyed the hike!

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: It's really lovelyüòç place. Highly recommended for running /walking at morning.. Please be careful, sometimes you may find snakes. Don't go too deep inside the hill especially when it's dark..

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: A place for those who loves to have an adventure in the nature side of Singapore. You can hike, cycle through the designated trails. Bring along family ad friends for a great adventure together. I don‚Äôt know how many times I‚Äôve been, but this place has always been the best spot to go to. There are places that are challenging which I love.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Bukit timah nature reserve is the place you go to experience Singapore flora and fauna. It is home to Bukit Timah Hill, the highest point of Singapore at 164m above sea level. With a keen eye, you would be able spot the wild animals (be quiet as you can scare them away with your voice). There are a few trails for your choosing that you can select based on your hiking experience. Experience the fresh rainforest air while getting a good workout. Would recommend a trip for both soloists and for the whole family.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
This is beauty of amazing city Singapore.
One thing to praise - despite being a small country, the presence of such nature parks to help the biodiversity prosper is commendable.
Must visit place. Beautiful place for hike.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
19 June 2021 cloudy
From Jurong Lake Gardens to rail corridor, then Singapore Quarry. Completed my 25th half marathon in 2021.

Moderately tough hiking trail

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Best place for trekking and day trip to get away from stressful city life. You will experience a real wild life taste and well maintained forest. Trails are nice and the height of the mountain is just nice especially for age above 40+ üëç

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
Bukit Timah Nature Reserve is one of the very few in the world that is located within an urban city.  It,s also the highest hill in Singapore standing at 163M above sea level . This tropical rainforest has one of the richest and most diverse ecological systems , visitors can see variety of plants , animals  and insects. A  very good place for nature lovers to relax as well as for academics to do research.This is also a good spot for Shinrin -Yoku ( forest bathing ) in the early morning .Early bird catches the good ions produced by the trees which can help to alleviate depression , relieve stress and boost energy .    The nearest train station is Beauty World MRT Station. Bus services that go there are 67 , 75 , 170 , 171 ,184 ,852 and 961 . The 2 nearest bus stop are code number 42109 which is opposite Beauty World Centre( Alight at Jalan Anak Bukit ) and the other bus stop code number 42091 which is opposite Bukit Timah Shopping Centre ( Alight at Upper Bukit Timah Road )  .A gentle reminder to all visitors. As a mark of respect , please be kind and gentle to all plants and animals which you may encounter along the way. Please also refrain from littering ( especially soiled sanitary napkin stained with blood ) , spitting or uninating inside the Nature Reserve , so as to avoid offending the Guardian God of the mountain commonly known as  Keramat Datuk Kong in Singapore , Malaysia , Indonesia and Southern Thailand . Keramat Datuk Kong usually lives in trees , caves , hill top , lakes  , ponds , strange funny looking rock/stone formation , termite nests ( mould ) as well as in the form of tomb of past  holy men or heroes inside forest and jungle. I would strongly like to caution those female hikers who are having their period  not to sit on any big rock or touch any big tree trunk . Of all the Keramat Datuk Kong , the Green Faced Datuk Kong is the most fearsome among them and is much dreaded by hikers , mountain guides , tree cutters , park rangers and even the native aborigines like Orang Asli and Dayak in Malaysia. Anyone who offends the Green Faced Datuk Kong will usually end up in tragic death or prolong illnesses.
I strongly believe that wherever we are and wherever we go , we must always respect the local residents  ,  local deities and spirits residing there. Before going up to any mountain , I will always put both my hands together  in prayer position and say like this : " Dear Mountain God( or Datuk Kong ) and all other spirits dwelling in this mountain , please kindly excuse me for troubling you by intruding into your territory. I harbour no evil intention and merely coming here to enjoy the fresh air and nice scenery . Please kindly grant me permission to enter your territory . Thank you very much ."
You may say it aloud or silently inside your heart. It is the thought that counts !
In case any hiker is lost in any mountain at night ,  just stay calm and seek shelter under a safe place. In the worst scenario if you feel any unfriendly spiritual being is advancing toward you , just chant the mantra  of White Umbrella Goddess which goes like this :
" Hom Mama Hom Ni Soha ". After chanting 7x , take out a pen or any object and blow the mantra on the pen / object, use the pen/object to draw a circle on the ground to surround yourself .This act of drawing a circle and keeping yourself inside the circle is called setting boundary . Keep chanting this mantra constantly to invoke more power from White Umbrella Goddess , also known as Sitatapatra or Dukkar Buddha in Tibetan , most likely the unfriendly spiritual being will leave you alone .
I would recommend all hikers anywhere in the world to inform their friends or family members before setting out to any mountain and bringing along  torch light , sufficient food and water ration as well as wearing religious amulet , talisman or any other protection items depending on your religion .

P/S : For Bukit Timah Nature Reserve , just a bottle of plain water will do. Opening hrs : 7am to 7pm daily.  No visitor is allowed to stay overnight after 7pm . No entrance fee.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
It is a good 1.5 h hike.
There is quite a lot of elevation.
You will encounter monkeys, wild boar (mostly in the evening), birds and small wildlife.
The forest is dense hence it is not hot at all .
Definitely a nice way to spend the weekend morning .

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: This is a popular park with many trying to squeeze in over the weekends. The carpark, though adequate, is still full by 7am in the weekends. Otherwise, notice beats the fresh air here locally.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Some steep challenging climbs for a middle aged man like me. But overall doable. Parking can easily get full at certain times. Try the dairy farm loop right near the summit.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
Great nature hike. Ascend starts with a steep pathed slope, follow by gradual path. Final summit ascend calls for the brave to take the steep steps up which could be quite an effort to take in one single burst of strength. Alternatively, take the slightly longer gradual pathed slope to the top.
No breathtaking top view, but the journey to the summit is filled with florals & wildlife. Keep a look out for them.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Great trekking experience. One can try the trails of either upslope incline all the way to the summit or into the forest trails loops. Follow the signboard for difficulty level but one can be confused as I thought it keads to Dairy Farm Nature Reserve but in the end its a one round trip back to the same spot. Pls note inside the trails, there are multiple steps and its steep and high not for beginners. Confirming you will sweat for those whom wants adrenaline to clear your endorphins. For coast to coast trail (PCNs), pls use the main route and it may lead to Railway Mall and other parks such as Bukit Batok Nature Park. A great path to glock your running miles too!

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Couldn‚Äôt believe this much nature could be found in SG. It‚Äôs like walking through a wardrobe to Narnia.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Went in the mid afternoon and it was still relatively quite pack with people. Great place, many routes to take to summit. Ranging from easy to difficult, and the difficult routes are mainly filled with stairs. But overall, even if you have very little to no exercise experiences, still an easy trek up since it‚Äôs a very short. Beautiful place to enjoy the nature and there are a few trail paths to take!

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: A truly natural park. Wet all around. You can also meet the lovely squirrels jumping around. Facilities for children are quite interesting. Justin watch out for the mosquito, otherwise you will be their lunch:) Fully recommend for family.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Walked past Singapore‚Äôs history when this place was home to largest granite stone quarry supply. Now this beautiful is taken back by flora and fauna in their own way making wetlands, home to monitor lizards, monitor flies. A nice place for light trekking in the woods away from city hustle bustle ‚ù§Ô∏è

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
Very nice nature reserve with plenty of interesting flora and fauna. There is a guided nature appreciation walk every month where you can learn about the reserve. You can register through the national parks website for the walk and it‚Äôs free of cost.

The trek has some steep paths and has plenty of monkeys. Do not carry plastics as it affects the environment and most likely will be snatched by the monkey.

The visitors center is well maintained and informative. The facilities and toilets are good as well.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
Nice place for hiking.

Near beauty world MRT station.

It take almost half an hour to reach the summit if we walk in normal speed.

The summit is at height of 163.63 ft.

At the starting point the path is very steep.
Keep your confidence high and start hiking go slow for ease, it's not at all steep after 10 min hiking.

From summit there are various trails if you want to continue.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
As Singapore continues to grow as a nation, it's nice that green spaces like this is maintain in the midst of our urban concrete jungle.

There are a handful of trails to take as you allow the lush nature envelopes you in her warm balmy embrace.

Let it lead you to open expense of field with a backdrop of rock quarry. Or wander into the canopy of trees offering some shade.

With the highest peak at about 163m, the climb can be as easy or as difficult you want it to be. Just have a comfortable pair of shoes and a water bladder or bottle to stay hydrated.

Outdoor enthusiasts can also try mountain biking or rock climbing. You can also take the opportunity to soak in some history of this place and Singapore at the Exhibition Hall.

Map of the nature reserve can be found near several spot telling you exactly where you are and where you can continue exploration.

Creature comforts like food court are within reach at the foot of the hill for a well deserved meal or drink.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
A must-go place if you are in Singapore, especially in the morning. Different plants and animals are around you when you're totally immersed in a world of nature. If you walk slowly and observe around carefully, many small items will give you a surprise.

Facilities are conveinient at the foot of hill and on your way.

Personally, the only two places you must go are the lake and the hill top.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
Nice place for a simple hike would take about 30-45 at strolling pace.
Update on the comment above- there are several routes to be taken and if you take the main road up it should take the suggested times.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: No admission fee. The highest mountain in Singapore. An hour is enough to get to the top. Great scenery is a bonus.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
A nice hike that's not too strenuous.

If you are looking for an easy hike this one is for you.  It's not too steep or long and it's completely shaded by tree canopy.  The trail itself is free but you do pay a small bit for parking.  The main path is wide and made of rough concrete so its safe even when wet from rain.  The main path also doesn't include stairs so they are safe for almost anyone.  Going at a normal pace I think it took around an hour round trip.  The scenery is made up of thick vegetation with an occasional monkey or squirrel sighting.

All and all this was a pleasurable side trip if you have the extra time for a hike

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Had so much fun here. Great view of the quary site. The water in the pond or lake was so clear that we are able to see the fishes and turtles swimming freely. The visitors area is clean and very welcoming. Small crocs scared the hell out of me which was one of the higlight of our nature tripping. Reaching the summit was very rewarding. I will surely come back here.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Very nice place for jogging or walking, surprisingly such natural view in the city country. Love it.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Beautiful place for a morning walk. Peaceful and serene, one of the many oases in Singapore. Initial climb up is steep but it gets a lot easier more than halfway up to the ‚Äòsummit‚Äô. Watch out of the monkeys!

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Had wonderful experience .. done trekking for 9 KM and explored whole reserve.. recommendations are carry good amount of water, light snacks.. advised to visit in the morning and come out by lunch time.. you have lot of hawker centers for all cuisines ..

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve

There were also many paths for us to explore. I even went around there and at the visitor center, there is a 3D view of the entire Bukit Timah nature reserve. 5 stars

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Lovely forest trail not too far from the city. The gradient is steep on the main route but there are alternate easier routes to take. Well maintained. Look out for some nocturnal creatures like the Malayan Colugo sleeping on the trees.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: While the main track leading from Visitor‚Äôs Centre to the 163.63m Bukit Timah Summit is very popular with the public, with both young and old burning calories to scale Singapore‚Äôs highest hill, it is often difficult for wildlife enthusiasts to spot interesting animals along this stretch due to the human traffic and noise. For me who develops a passion for photographing wildlife, I prefer the quieter ambience of outlying trails such as Catchment Path, Cave Path and Pipeline Trial. With patience, I was rewarded with sightings of the green crested lizard, branded imperial butterfly and greater racket-tailed drongo. The rich biodiversity of Singapore‚Äôs wildlife is best exemplified by the central catchment nature reserve, where animals thrive within lush forested areas.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve

review_text: Good exercise just to walk up hill. Only 1.2km but sure is steep. No rush, if your doctor does not think you should stress yourself, please listen to your doctor. There are many trails do enjoy discovering the old Kampong Trail to Rifle Range Road.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Singapore highest hill. Good spot for nature lovers and hikers. Saw 1 iguana,  2 snakes, 2 monkeys along the pathways. The quarry forms a beautiful scenery, a spot to go to when you are there. Reconnect with nature. Nearest MRT: Beauty World.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: A perfect place for hikes on weekends. Depending on your stamina you can choose levels of hike. Check out the map near the park entrance. Best if you visit in the morning. The initial slope is steep but towards the summit it's moderate. If you are lucky, you may see some monkeys. Things to bring - water bottle (fill it near entrance, later you may not find water fountain), napkin and good walking shoes. There are some vending machines near left side of information center.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: For those who want a break from the high rise concrete of Singapore, this is a must see! Nestled near the heart of Singapore, this is a wonderfully marked walk/hike. It does have some steep elevation changes so likely more for those in decent cardio shape. The rock quarry lakes are beautiful to grasp. The trails are well marked and you might be lucky enough to see monkeys along the way. A fun outing for nature lovers or those looking for some fitbit steps! Choose the South View Track and we will have a nice high-tree and sounds of the birds.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: It's a wonderful place, has several trails, that are mildly challenging and well marked. There are rest spots and washrooms. It's possible to go all the way to the Dairy Farm side. There are mountain bike trails as well. A place for people of all ages. Some of the visitors could be a bit more mindful though.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
Great place to enjoy original forest in Singapore and doing some easy trek. There is many path, divided by difficult. Each one would take around 1.5 hour. Since paper map are not given due to ecology reason, just take a pic of the park map at the entrance.
All along the path there's many road sign and map so it will be easy to walk through any path you will choose.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Nice hike! Has routes with different difficulties and maps to follow them. Come really early if you want to see monkeys. And stay on the trail if you don't want to meet a snake.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
This nature reserve has the tallest hill and natural elevation in Singapore. It is one of the few primary rainforest in Singapore.

There are many monkeys living in the reserve. Be careful when taking out or eating food as they might come near you to take the food.

The path to the summit is well built with many steps to the top it is generally not too steep and children may also climb the hill relatively easily. There are many paths with varying difficulty for different people with different levels of experience.

The nature reserve has also many animals which are explained and described by the signboards in the nature reserve.

Overall it is a good place to breathe in fresh air and to take a break in nature.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
One of the few wild nature places left in Singapore. Walk, hike, run, to enjoy nature.
There are many trails of varying difficulty. Even the hardest won't take more than a few hours. They are well marked and close to amenities such as toilets. Mobile reception is available, on almost all of the trails.
Please observe simple trail etiquette such as keeping to the left, giving way to people going uphill, etc. And of course, keep the noise down, don't blast your music, no littering, etc.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Beautiful and safe nature reserve. Good place to workout and the view from the top of the hill is Amazing. You can feel the pure and natural air. Overall a must visit place I'm SG

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Singapore can be hot and humid. We chose a bad day to go here, but it was still OK. We entered from car park A ( one of the three car parks ) and made our way to the quarry which offers a rare view in the mostly urban Singapore. The walk is mostly paved so not a authentic experience of a trail but the best one can get in Singapore. There are several dirt tracks for biking but hiking isn't allowed on those. Overall it was nice. Saw several insects, monitor lizards and monkeys. While it's not a "Good" trail it's a great place to get away from the urban environment of Singapore. Recommended to everyone at least once.

The upwards sloping of the trail might not be for everyone, some parts are rather steep and could be cause for worry. Overall, a decent weekend outing or an exercise routine for most.

You can start both from Hindede drive car park, go first to the summit and then down to quarry or for a better challenge start from Hillview mrt, take the Wallace trail behind the Salvation army, go first to the quarry, then come back a bit and  follow the signal to climb up to the summit!! name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
The highest mountain of the island.

=======
Bukit Timah, which dominates the
arterial Bukit Timah and Dunearn
Roads leading to the city, was
strategically important point for both
the Allied troops and the Japanese.

On the night of 10th February 1942,
the Japanese troops from the 5th and
18th Divisions, supported by armour,
attacked troops of the 11th and 15th
Indian Brigades, the 22nd Australian
Brigade, the Special Reserve Battalion,
Tomforce, Merrett's Force, the Argylls,
Jind State Infantry and X'Battalion. The Allied forces had to re-group to defend the critical junctions at Choa Chu Kang,
Jurong and Clementi Roads leading to Bukit Timah Road.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: An excellent trail! The forest canopy provides the cover you need from sun and rain. Bring at least 600ml of water - you will lose a lot in perspiration ascending the summit. The grade is relatively steep when following the non-tarmac trail, so expect to get a great interval workout, regardless of you walk or jog.  A little advice: take your headphones off if you‚Äôre accustomed to running or walking with music on - the Natural sounds coming from the forest surrounding you needs to be appreciated. I believe it makes it more enjoyable.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
Very beautiful and exceptionally clean nature park, full of an incredible diversity of plants and trees.
Do note though that several trails are closed due to renovation or accidents (in particular the entire yellow trail route is closed due to a landslide at time of reviewing).
The question I wanna ask though: why are there so many stairs? I have climbed up and down several hundreds of steps! And some of the steps are so high like 30cm and more? Are those "difficult" trails exclusively for a variety of men-spiders?
Nonetheless, a few very nice spots and definitely worth it if you like rainforest and good hiking.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
Always a fun outing for families, joggers and trekkers alike. Bird watchers, not so much. There are multiple paths that you could embark on ranging from "easy" to "difficult". After the restoration work in around 2015-2016, trekking is made much safer now with reinforced concrete slabs along the path to prevent soil corrosion. Safer doesn't mean it's easier though, depending on which path. For the challenged, there's a Rock Path that looks like you're going down (or up) a cliff. At this time of writing (nov-17) that path is closed, so do check beforehand if that's your main purpose of visiting BTNR.

Cave Path takes you past 2 "cave" entrances, which look like they're locked and not accessible. Hopefully it will be opened to public in future.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve

review_text: 30 years living in Singapore and I‚Äôve not once stepped foot on the only hill here - that was until Covid struck and I was forced to find alternative activities to occupy some hours of my week to keep myself sane. I found that respite in Bukit Timah Nature Reserve which i Guess is something to be thankful for. I‚Äôve been hiking amongst lesser crowds, enjoying sceneries of a bright and clear blue sky, breathing in crispier and fresher air. As I build up my endurance level week by week, sweating buckets ascending up the steeper steps, I find life just slightly more bearable and cultivating a mindset to not sweat the small stuff in life (pun intended). ü•∞

The walkway is steep but there are railings on the sides to hold and walk. Some ppl were doing scissor walking too.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text:
Bukit Timah Hill, located in its namesake district of¬†Bukit Timah, is a hill located near the geographical centre of¬†Singapore. The hill stands at an altitude of 164 metres (538 ft) above sea level, making it the highest natural peak in the country.

The hill‚Äôs elevation made Bukit Timah an important target for the Japanese during the Second World War, providing a tactical vantage point that the invading troops wanted.

Bukit Timah is one of the areas that witnessed the Japanese invasion during World War II, and was also where the British surrendered on 15 February 1942, marking the start of the Japanese Occupation of Singapore.

The Bukit Timah Nature Reserve is a small 1.64 square kilometre (400 acre) nature reserve near the geographic centre of the city-state of Singapore, located on the slopes of Bukit Timah Hill,

Singapore's highest hill standing at a height of 163.63 metres, and parts of the surrounding area.

Bukit Timah Nature Reserve was officially declared an ASEAN Heritage Park on 18 October 2011.

Nature Reserve Opening Hours
7am to 7pm daily (entering or remaining in the nature reserve after 7pm is not allowed)

Exhibition Hall Opening Hours
8am to 5.30pm daily

Many might go there in the morning to escape from the afternoon scorching sun, but the vast amount of trees will keep one cool regardless.
The idea timing to go to avoid crowds would be in the afternoon during cooling weather. Evening time would be idea during hotter weather.

Proper sports shoes or running shoes will be a great help. This was my first time here. I find going up the slope rather difficult and exhausting probably because I seldom exercise. However, after the initial climb, the slope became gentler and I had no trouble walking further inward but I didn't complete my climb because a fellow jogger told me the place would be closed at 7 pm.
I understand this reserve is a popular spot for locals and expatriates to brisk walk and jog. I also saw some enthusiastic cyclists.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: This place is a family favorite. If you love nature animals, and easy hikes, this is the place to go. Did you know that tigers used to roam these jungles up until about 100 years ago? While there are no more tigers, there still are many beautiful wild birds, lizards and squirrels and adorable monkeys to see. There are paved and unpaved paths to walk on. It‚Äôs also a great place to go jogging too. I recommend going early before it gets too hot outside.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: The nature reserve is home to Singapore's highest peak at roughly a hundred and sixty meters. It's a great place to walk around and explore the nature on offer. The biodiversity and animal species you can see if you choose to be vigilant are incredible. The hike is not particularly strenuous and you should watch out for monitor lizards because they are everywhere and easy to come in contact with. There's lots of parking and the nature reserve is relatively easy to get to. It can be quite busy on weekends but is it really nice way to get out and enjoy a different part of Singapore. If you take a particular route you can head down towards the Singapore quarry and Dairy Farms which give you a slightly different scenery and very often near the quarry there are lots of monkeys.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
review_text: Really great. Something we must conserve at all cost since it's our last remaining piece of primary jungle in a hill setting. The educational signs are illuminating and easy to understand. The climb to the top is tough but rewarding as there's so much to see and enjoy along the way. It's great that things are left as they are eg fallen trees, leaf litter etc just as it is in the wild.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve

There is a cemented path guiding you through the reserve to the top. Don't take safety for granted, bring torch lights at night or in the wee hours. Recommended to bathe yourself in insect repellent before starting the hike. Bring your own water bottles.
